of reporting.

30:45.310 --> 30:48.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kurt Eichenwald from "Newsweek,"
we thank
you.

30:48.213 --> 30:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KURT EICHENWALD: Thanks for
having me.

30:53.652 --> 31:02.894 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Stay with us.

31:02.928 --> 31:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": how
to parse
truth from lies in the digital
age; and an

31:08.166 --> 31:13.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inside look at the brand-new
National Museum
of African American History and
Culture.

31:13.538 --> 31:15.307 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Miles O'Brien

31:15.340 --> 31:19.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: In the aftermath of
this week's
bombings in New York and New
Jersey, science

31:19.111 --> 31:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
correspondent Miles O'Brien
looks at the ways
police departments are coming to
rely on bomb-disarming

31:25.484 --> 31:26.451 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
robots.

31:26.485 --> 31:28.820 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of our weekly Leading
Edge series.

31:28.854 --> 31:31.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Everybody, get off the
street!

31:31.990 --> 31:37.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: As the pipe and
pressure cooker
bomb plot unfolded and unraveled
in New York

31:37.696 --> 31:43.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and New Jersey, police deployed
some remotely
operated tools aimed at saving
the lives of

31:43.335 --> 31:48.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
civilians and bomb squad
technicians alike.

31:48.173 --> 31:54.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In New Jersey, a reminder of the
hair-trigger
risk they face in harm's way.

31:54.312 --> 32:02.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At NYPD bomb squad headquarters
on City Island
a few years ago, Lieutenant Mark
Torre gave

32:02.387 --> 32:08.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me a demo using the same robot,
the Remotec
ANDROS F6A, built by Northrop
Grumman.

32:08.927 --> 32:10.662 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

32:10.695 --> 32:12.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK TORRE, New York Police
Department: Its
primary mission is to put
distance between

32:12.397 --> 32:15.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our technicians and something of
a hazardous
nature, because distance in this
business

32:15.767 --> 32:17.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is always your friend.

32:17.536 --> 32:22.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In this scenario,
it is believed
there may be an explosive in
this car.

32:22.874 --> 32:25.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it is much more than a
hypothetical.

32:25.343 --> 32:30.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's what happened in Times
Square on May
1 of 2010.

32:30.515 --> 32:36.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A street vendor discovered a
smoldering, abandoned
car filled with propane tanks,
fertilizer,

32:36.955 --> 32:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
gasoline and firecrackers.

32:39.991 --> 32:45.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a Saturday evening, the
busiest time
of the week, in one of the
busiest, and most

32:45.163 --> 32:47.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
iconic, intersections in the
world.

32:47.098 --> 32:50.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MITCH SILBER, Former NYPD
Director of Intelligence
Analysis: Between the scenery,
the symbolism,

32:50.869 --> 32:58.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the congestion and it being be
just media
central for New York City, you
can't get much

32:58.410 --> 33:00.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
better of a background for
terrorists.

33:00.145 --> 33:06.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Mitch Silber was
NYPD's director
of intelligence analysis at the
time.

33:06.518 --> 33:11.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He shudders to think what would
have happened
if the car bomb, built by
Pakistani American

33:11.356 --> 33:14.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Faisal Shahzad, had not been a
dud.

33:14.559 --> 33:21.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MITCH SILBER: It would ripped
the car in half,
and this is a very busy
intersection.

33:21.700 --> 33:27.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Depending on the congestion of
people right
around the car, it would
certainly kill people,

33:27.038 --> 33:29.374 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
injured and maimed many others.

33:29.407 --> 33:34.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it would have been the first
big terrorist
attack in New York City since
9/11, since

33:34.579 --> 33:36.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
2001, nine years earlier.

33:36.348 --> 33:39.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, if he had
just been a better
bomb-maker, it would have been a
horrible

33:39.551 --> 33:40.518 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
event?

33:40.552 --> 33:42.454 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MITCH SILBER: Absolutely.

33:42.487 --> 33:48.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In fact, a few
months later,
the FBI built an identical car
bomb and detonated

33:48.460 --> 33:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it to see what could have
happened, a scary
thought.

33:55.133 --> 34:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, in Times Square, the
NYPD bomb squad
deployed its ANDROS robot and
did pretty much

34:02.207 --> 34:03.375 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what you are about to see.

34:03.408 --> 34:04.776 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DET.

34:04.809 --> 34:06.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES SCHUTTA, New York Police
Department:
Bomb squad is called.

34:06.645 --> 34:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A perimeter is set up, and we
are now going
to use this robot to approach
this vehicle

34:11.583 --> 34:13.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and take a look at what's
inside.

34:13.919 --> 34:20.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Detective James
Schutta operated
the robot from a safe distance.

34:20.058 --> 34:21.126 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DET.

34:21.159 --> 34:23.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES SCHUTTA: We are not in
sight of the
vehicle.

34:23.061 --> 34:27.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key to successful robot
operation is that
he can do the entire job without
ever seeing

34:27.899 --> 34:29.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what the robot is actually
doing.

34:29.301 --> 34:31.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's all done remotely via the
cameras.

34:31.937 --> 34:36.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But this robot is
more than
just a remote-controlled eye.

34:36.574 --> 34:43.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is able to get inside the car
to take a
closer look.

34:43.715 --> 34:47.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The robot fired a .12-gauge
blast through
both windows.

34:47.085 --> 34:48.286 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DET.

34:48.320 --> 34:50.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES SCHUTTA: And that's what
we call a perfect
shot.

34:50.055 --> 34:54.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is sort of just a game of
manipulation
now, where he's going to
maneuver the robot

34:54.693 --> 34:56.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
until we get a better view of
what's inside.

34:56.761 --> 34:59.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He took out both windows.

34:59.097 --> 35:01.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now we have an opportunity to
look in both
sides.

35:01.433 --> 35:07.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In this scenario,
the robot
discovered there is indeed a
bomb inside the

35:07.906 --> 35:08.873 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
car.

35:08.907 --> 35:10.375 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DET.

35:10.408 --> 35:13.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES SCHUTTA: We always try to
put ourselves
in the mind of the bomber.

35:13.178 --> 35:15.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We want to stay one step ahead
of them.

35:15.380 --> 35:19.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The bomb itself really has sort
of remained
the same throughout the years.

35:19.117 --> 35:22.253 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's what sets them off that
sets them apart.

35:22.287 --> 35:27.592 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The more sophisticated
triggering systems,
they're difficult to defeat, and
that's a

35:27.625 --> 35:30.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
concern to us, but, again, we
always try to
stay one step ahead.

35:30.762 --> 35:38.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Remotec robots
are also used
by the military to defuse bombs,
but also

35:38.636 --> 35:43.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to kill insurgents hiding in
alleys.

35:44.009 --> 35:48.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Dallas in July, that same
tactic was used
by police.

35:48.313 --> 35:54.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A robot blew up a cornered
sniper who had
taken aim at white police
officers, killing

35:54.152 --> 35:55.687 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
five of them.

35:55.720 --> 35:59.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was unprecedented in U.S. law
enforcement
history.

35:59.457 --> 36:02.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But Dallas Police Chief David
Brown said he
had no regrets.

36:02.961 --> 36:04.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROWN, Dallas Police
Chief: I would
do it again.

36:04.929 --> 36:07.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would do it again to save our
officers'
lives.

36:07.832 --> 36:12.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But experts who
track the evolution
of technology used by the
military and law

36:12.937 --> 36:18.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enforcement worry an important
threshold has
been crossed, without a national
debate on

36:18.810 --> 36:20.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the ethical issues.

36:20.678 --> 36:25.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER W. SINGER, Robotics
Expert: The question
is, is it going to be viewed as
an anomaly,

36:25.350 --> 36:28.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or is it a precedent that will
be followed
more widely?

36:28.820 --> 36:34.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Peter W. Singer
is an expert
on unmanned and robotic weapons
systems.

36:34.626 --> 36:39.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says it is inevitable local
police will
increase their use of robots.

36:39.230 --> 36:44.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER W. SINGER: The question is
not, are
police going to be using robotic
systems?

36:44.035 --> 36:45.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's, how?

36:45.537 --> 36:46.771 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
In what manner?

36:46.805 --> 36:48.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How will they be trained to use
them?

36:48.339 --> 36:50.175 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How will they be regulated?

36:50.208 --> 36:51.709 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Will they be armed or not?

36:51.743 --> 36:55.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they're armed, will they be
lethally armed
or with non-lethal weapons?

36:55.513 --> 37:01.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The issue has to involve not
just the police,
but also the populace, the
people that are

37:01.219 --> 37:07.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be protected and served by
the police and
the tools, including the robotic
ones, that

37:07.092 --> 37:08.827 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they use.

37:08.860 --> 37:13.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The devices used
in New York,
New Jersey and Dallas all still
have human

37:13.231 --> 37:17.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beings in the loop driving the
robot, making
the decisions.

37:18.002 --> 37:23.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But as robots become more
autonomous, defining
some clear rules of engagement
will become

37:23.274 --> 37:28.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a more urgent concern for law
enforcement
and the public.

37:28.246 --> 37:34.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," New York.

37:34.285 --> 37:47.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We all realize we
are inundated
by electronic data, whether we
are at work,

37:47.832 --> 37:51.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
school, home or play, but how to
make sense
of it all?

37:51.503 --> 37:55.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the focus of the latest
addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

37:55.340 --> 37:56.841 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown leads the way.

37:56.875 --> 38:00.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: "It ain't what
you don't know
that gets you into trouble.

38:00.545 --> 38:03.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's what you know for sure that
just ain't
so."

38:03.681 --> 38:05.450 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mark Twain said that.

38:05.483 --> 38:08.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And imagine what he would make
of the Internet,
when everything is available and
we're sure

38:08.820 --> 38:09.854 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we know so much.

38:09.888 --> 38:11.556 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But do we?

38:11.589 --> 38:16.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Twain quote appears at the
beginning of
a new book titled "A Field Guide
to Lies:

38:16.094 --> 38:18.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Critical Thinking in the
Information Age."

38:18.263 --> 38:23.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our guide is Daniel Levitin, a
neuroscientist
and bestselling author of books,
including

38:23.468 --> 38:26.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"This Is Your Brain on Music"
and "The Organized
Mind."

38:26.738 --> 38:28.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And, Dan, welcome to you.

38:28.473 --> 38:32.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Your starting point, we're
bombarded with
information, but it's harder
than ever to

38:32.076 --> 38:33.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
know what's true.

38:33.778 --> 38:34.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN, Author, "A Field
Guide to
Lies: Critical Thinking in the
Information

38:34.946 --> 38:36.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Age": We're making more and more
decisions
every day.

38:36.047 --> 38:37.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think a lot of us feel
overloaded by the
process.

38:37.982 --> 38:43.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as you say, it's getting
harder and harder
to know, when you find things on
the Internet,

38:43.254 --> 38:44.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what you can believe and what
you can't.

38:44.756 --> 38:47.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there isn't really anybody
doing it for
us.

38:47.358 --> 38:49.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you see this
everywhere.

38:49.661 --> 38:54.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You go through both data,
numbers, and -- and,
well, everything, right?

38:54.465 --> 38:56.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Yes.

38:56.100 --> 39:00.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it's in Facebook and in
statistics
and in things that politicians
say.

39:00.838 --> 39:03.174 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's in headlines.

39:03.208 --> 39:05.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's in representations that a
salesman might
make to you.

39:05.877 --> 39:07.245 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's everywhere.

39:07.278 --> 39:08.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's clearly
annoying you,
right, as a scientist.

39:08.479 --> 39:10.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You don't -- you just don't like
this world.

39:10.281 --> 39:12.050 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

39:12.083 --> 39:17.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Well, I like a
world where
each of us has the tools to be
able to make

39:17.121 --> 39:19.023 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
able to make our own decisions.

39:19.057 --> 39:23.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think I'm always right,
but I would
like to empower people to come
to sound conclusions

39:23.361 --> 39:26.965 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
using a systematic way of
looking at things.

39:26.998 --> 39:30.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so a
very simple
-- you give a bunch of examples
in your book.

39:30.168 --> 39:34.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A very simple one is the pie
chart, right,
of polling that we're hit with a
lot of the

39:34.839 --> 39:35.807 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
time.

39:35.840 --> 39:37.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Yes.

39:37.675 --> 39:38.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is from --
this happens
to be FOX News, but it could --
in 2012 -- and

39:38.810 --> 39:41.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it could be probably from any
time and any
network.

39:41.946 --> 39:42.914 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Yes.

39:42.947 --> 39:43.915 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, look at this.

39:43.948 --> 39:45.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tell us what we're seeing here.

39:45.750 --> 39:49.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Well, the first
rule of pie
charts, Jeff, is that you're
taking a pie,

39:49.120 --> 39:50.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're dividing it up into
pieces.

39:50.922 --> 39:52.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The pieces have to add up to 100
percent.

39:52.624 --> 39:53.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

39:53.625 --> 39:54.692 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's the idea.

39:54.726 --> 39:55.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: And, as you see
here, they
don't.

39:55.727 --> 39:57.428 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, you can imagine how this
happens.

39:57.462 --> 40:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The kind of people who become
graphic artists
may not be mathematically
inclined.

40:02.200 --> 40:04.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're artists, artistically
inclined.

40:04.435 --> 40:06.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so you end up with things
like this.

40:06.271 --> 40:10.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But the missing
information
-- you could also look at that
and say -- I'm

40:10.074 --> 40:14.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to imagine what -- maybe
people were
asked -- they were told they
could they could

40:14.679 --> 40:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
favor several candidates, right?

40:16.814 --> 40:18.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Well, that's
right.

40:18.283 --> 40:19.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But, somehow,
that's not shown
in what we're looking at.

40:19.751 --> 40:20.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Right.

40:20.818 --> 40:23.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Who would you support for the
upcoming election?

40:23.821 --> 40:25.623 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you're allowed to name more
than one.

40:25.657 --> 40:27.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so you get something like
this that adds
up to 100.

40:27.925 --> 40:30.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in that case, you shouldn't
use a pie
chart.

40:30.595 --> 40:34.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really visually deceptive,
which might
lead you to conclude the wrong
thing.

40:34.866 --> 40:38.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
another example
you give, sometimes one truth
hiding another,

40:38.803 --> 40:40.638 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a less favorable truth.

40:40.672 --> 40:47.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is showing Apple,
right, and Tim
Cook, the CEO, talking about
sales that actually

40:47.812 --> 40:48.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
went down, right?

40:48.813 --> 40:49.914 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Yes.

40:49.947 --> 40:50.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But he didn't
want us to know
that.

40:50.815 --> 40:51.783 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

40:51.816 --> 40:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: This is one of
my favorite.

40:53.651 --> 40:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what do you do when you have
got something,
a case like this, where the
sales have gone

40:56.654 --> 40:58.656 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
down, and a graph would clearly
show it?

40:58.690 --> 41:03.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, you create a cumulative
sales graph,
where, as long as you sold only
one unit,

41:03.895 --> 41:06.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the graph is going to appear to
go up.

41:06.664 --> 41:10.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if your sales for the
quarter are down,
you can hide it this way.

41:10.535 --> 41:12.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's what he did.

41:12.303 --> 41:15.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now, the biggest
source of
information, of course, for all
of -- in our

41:15.239 --> 41:17.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
own lives now is the Internet,
right?

41:17.108 --> 41:22.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you write about a -- I think
you call
it an anti-skepticism bias.

41:22.347 --> 41:27.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We believe so much of what comes
to us on
the Internet.

41:27.151 --> 41:28.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now, I wonder why.

41:28.953 --> 41:30.555 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You're a neuroscientist.

41:30.588 --> 41:34.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, what's going on to make
us not skeptical
enough?

41:34.559 --> 41:37.195 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: You know, I
don't really know.

41:37.228 --> 41:38.996 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:39.030 --> 41:42.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: I mean, part of
it is that,
when we have learned something,
there's this

41:42.367 --> 41:44.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
thing called belief
perseverance.

41:44.369 --> 41:49.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Having learned something, we
tend to cling
to that belief, even in the face
of overwhelming

41:49.540 --> 41:51.776 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
evidence to the contrary.

41:51.809 --> 41:57.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New information comes in all
time, and the
thing we ought to be thinking
about doing

41:57.281 --> 42:00.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is changing our beliefs as that
new information
comes in.

42:00.385 --> 42:01.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's what
critical thinking
means.

42:02.019 --> 42:03.688 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: I think so.

42:03.721 --> 42:07.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to take a step back, and
realize that
not everything we encounter is
true.

42:07.692 --> 42:12.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You don't want to be gullibly
accepting everything
as true, but you don't want to
be cynically

42:12.263 --> 42:14.031 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rejecting everything as false.

42:14.065 --> 42:16.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You want to take your time to
evaluate the
information.

42:16.634 --> 42:21.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the end of the
day, don't
people -- don't we have to trust
institutions

42:21.906 --> 42:23.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or trust somebody?

42:23.107 --> 42:24.275 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Well, we do.

42:24.308 --> 42:25.843 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Of course, science is based on
this.

42:25.877 --> 42:29.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have never seen a proton or
electron spinning
around it.

42:29.414 --> 42:31.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have never actually seen a
chromosome.

42:31.816 --> 42:35.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I trust that they exist because
people who
I trust tell me they do.

42:35.953 --> 42:36.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

42:36.954 --> 42:38.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: It does come
down to that.

42:38.790 --> 42:43.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But we can be skeptical,
suitably skeptical,
and we can trust news outlets,
some more than

42:43.928 --> 42:44.896 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
others.

42:44.929 --> 42:46.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

42:46.564 --> 42:48.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: We -- I mean,
society functions
because we trust one another.

42:48.666 --> 42:51.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I trust that my plumber knows
what he's doing,
right?

42:51.235 --> 42:56.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, though, that we need to
be armed
with the critical thinking
skills that lawyers

42:56.874 --> 42:59.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and scientists and journalists
such as yourself
have.

42:59.777 --> 43:03.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We all need to have those as we
make our way
through the day.

43:03.247 --> 43:04.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they're not that hard to
acquire.

43:04.582 --> 43:07.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think they can be acquired in
a couple hours.

43:07.151 --> 43:10.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, before
I let you
go, we have to go back to that
Mark Twain

43:10.354 --> 43:11.422 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
quote.

43:11.456 --> 43:13.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to put that back up,
because I read
it.

43:13.291 --> 43:15.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I started it -- our segment.

43:15.126 --> 43:16.894 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You start your book with it.

43:16.928 --> 43:20.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you tell us in the end
of your book
-- and I'm going to tell our
audience -- that

43:20.631 --> 43:21.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
wasn't said by Mark Twain.

43:21.866 --> 43:22.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Right.

43:22.867 --> 43:24.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The quote ain't so.

43:24.302 --> 43:27.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's a wonderful example of
how we believe
things that aren't so.

43:27.505 --> 43:32.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, I agree with the
sentiment that
it's probably more dangerous to
believe some

43:32.977 --> 43:38.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things that aren't so than to
not believe
something -- you know, to
believe in a lie.

43:38.783 --> 43:44.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in the fact-checking for
the book, I
went to find -- as you do, I
went to find

43:44.589 --> 43:45.857 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the original source.

43:45.890 --> 43:48.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it was nowhere to be found
in any of Twain's
writings.

43:48.659 --> 43:51.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, Mark Twain
didn't say it.

43:51.395 --> 43:52.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Daniel Levitin lied.

43:52.830 --> 43:53.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The "NewsHour" lied.

43:53.831 --> 43:56.234 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we have now set the record
straight.

43:56.267 --> 43:57.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Which is how
things move forward.

43:57.468 --> 43:58.436 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

43:58.469 --> 43:59.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The book is "A Field Guide to
Lies."

44:00.004 --> 44:01.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Daniel Levitin, thanks very
much..

44:01.072 --> 44:08.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL LEVITIN: Thanks for
having me.

44:08.446 --> 44:19.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight, the
jewel in
the Smithsonian Museum crown
opens this weekend

44:19.690 --> 44:21.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the National Mall.

44:21.692 --> 44:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama will be on hand
to dedicate
the National Museum of African
American History

44:26.564 --> 44:27.832 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Culture.

44:27.865 --> 44:31.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We take you on a tour and show
how it all
came to be.

44:31.035 --> 44:34.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOYCE BAILEY, Museum Donor: We
can see she
has her camera right there.

44:34.839 --> 44:37.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was one of her photographic
days.

44:37.808 --> 44:41.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joyce Bailey's legacy turned out
to be worth
more than money.

44:41.512 --> 44:47.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her mother, Lois Alexander Lane
left her a
treasure trove from the museum
she created,

44:47.385 --> 44:54.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Harlem Institute of Fashion,
costumes,
dresses sewn and worn by slaves,
celebrities

44:54.458 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and by civil rights icons.

44:57.028 --> 45:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things I think people
are surprised
to know, or to remember, is that
Rosa Parks

45:01.132 --> 45:02.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was a seamstress.

45:02.133 --> 45:04.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOYCE BAILEY: Yes, she was.

45:04.068 --> 45:09.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was actually carrying the
dress that the
museum now has on the day that
she was arrested.

45:09.307 --> 45:14.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a beautiful yellow with
brown stripes
in it.

45:14.579 --> 45:15.813 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's beyond belief.

45:15.846 --> 45:17.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You really just have to see it.

45:17.782 --> 45:22.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Beginning this
weekend, thousands
of people will stream into the
brand-new National

45:22.420 --> 45:27.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Museum of African American
History and Culture
to see elements of Bailey's
collection and

45:27.692 --> 45:30.328 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
countless other priceless items.

45:30.361 --> 45:35.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is this, an airplane flown
cross-country
to the museum once piloted by
the all-black

45:35.967 --> 45:42.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tuskegee Airmen, the casket of
14-year-old
Emmett Till, lynched in 1955 for
whistling

45:42.740 --> 45:47.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at a white woman, the writings
of abolitionist
Frederick Douglass, shackles
discovered on

45:48.012 --> 45:54.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a sunken ship that brought
hundreds of slaves
to America, and from a South
Carolina plantation,

45:54.218 --> 46:00.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a fully restored slave cabin,
the dress Marian
Anderson wore when she sang at
the Lincoln

46:00.891 --> 46:06.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Memorial, and costumes from "The
Wiz," the
all-black Broadway musical based
on "The Wizard

46:06.397 --> 46:10.234 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Oz," donated from Joyce
Bailey's collection.

46:10.267 --> 46:15.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is as an amazing place,
chockful of the
expected and the expected.

46:15.339 --> 46:19.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
One thing missing, major
artifacts from the
Reverend Martin Luther King Jr.

46:19.744 --> 46:25.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His family apparently decided to
hold onto
some of the most famous
memorabilia, including

46:25.149 --> 46:30.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Bible that President Obama
used to take
the oath of office in 2013.

46:30.955 --> 46:36.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In any case, it fell to museum
director Lonnie
Bunch and his band of curators
to sort through

46:36.527 --> 46:38.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what turned into a rush of
donations.

46:38.596 --> 46:39.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH, Director, National
Museum of
African American History and
Culture: But,

46:39.930 --> 46:42.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when I saw them, I said, we are
going to tell
that story.

46:42.500 --> 46:46.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just love, from "The Wiz,"
I just love
how they look.

46:46.103 --> 46:47.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I just think they're so
distinctive.

46:47.872 --> 46:50.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They obviously speak volumes
about Geoffrey
Holder.

46:50.441 --> 46:53.110 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The designer.

46:53.144 --> 46:54.879 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: The designer.

46:54.912 --> 46:55.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, plus, they're just so
beautiful.

46:55.880 --> 46:56.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It was a big moment
at the time.

46:56.881 --> 46:58.649 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: Absolutely.

46:58.683 --> 47:02.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: From sobering
memorabilia like
rebellion leader Nat Turner's
Bible, to 20th

47:02.286 --> 47:08.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
century musical memories, Chuck
Berry's cherry
red Cadillac, and Parliament
Funkadelic's

47:08.125 --> 47:14.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
iconic Mothership, here lit up
and sheathed
in plastic in preparation for
the opening.

47:14.131 --> 47:18.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: During concerts,
it would come
down, and George Clinton would
get out.

47:18.235 --> 47:21.172 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it'd be this notion that he
was from another
planet.

47:21.205 --> 47:22.173 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

47:22.206 --> 47:23.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Which he kind of
was.

47:23.207 --> 47:25.009 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: Which he still is.

47:25.042 --> 47:29.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The $540 million
project, a century
in the making, and the first
green museum

47:29.180 --> 47:33.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the National Mall, captures
the sweep of
African-American history.

47:33.084 --> 47:34.919 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, what do we have here?

47:34.952 --> 47:37.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: This is one of my
great treasures.

47:37.688 --> 47:41.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What I love is what my staff is
able to find.

47:41.158 --> 47:47.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is a playbill from
Newcastle, England,
in 1857 that is from Ira
Aldridge's career.

47:48.032 --> 47:51.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ira Aldridge, the great black
thespian that
couldn't get jobs in the United
States as

47:51.936 --> 47:54.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a great actor, classical actor,
had to go
to Europe.

47:54.538 --> 47:58.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Othello, who
everyone now thinks
of as a character always played
by a black

47:58.075 --> 47:59.043 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
actor.

47:59.076 --> 48:00.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LONNIE BUNCH: Exactly.

48:00.077 --> 48:01.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But it was always in blackface.

48:01.645 --> 48:03.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Galleries are
devoted to breakthroughs
in sports and performance.

48:03.214 --> 48:08.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: The joy of Prince,
and I love
the Michael Jackson fedora.

48:08.452 --> 48:09.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I just capture that.

48:09.787 --> 48:11.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, obviously, the "Soul Train"
costume.

48:11.088 --> 48:13.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: "Soul Train" costume
is a little
alarming.

48:13.991 --> 48:15.259 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:15.292 --> 48:16.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: Well, it is,
because we thought
that was cool.

48:16.494 --> 48:17.561 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
GWEN IFILL: We.

48:17.595 --> 48:18.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't know about we.

48:18.729 --> 48:19.697 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:19.730 --> 48:20.698 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Speak for yourself.

48:20.731 --> 48:21.699 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:21.732 --> 48:23.634 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: This is cool.

48:23.667 --> 48:27.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bunch, a former president of the
Chicago Historical
Society, shepherded the project
to completion,

48:27.271 --> 48:33.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wooing Congress for half the
money, and soliciting
private donations from
millionaires like Oprah

48:33.043 --> 48:35.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Winfrey and philanthropist David
Rubenstein.

48:35.746 --> 48:42.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But he also appealed to
individuals, families,
churches, fraternities and
sororities, who

48:42.720 --> 48:49.026 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
handed over gems like James
Baldwin's inkwell
and Malcolm X's tape recorder.

48:49.059 --> 48:54.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Advance tickets flew out the
door, 5,000 of
them in 18 minutes one day.

48:54.565 --> 48:59.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On this journey you have been to
get to this
point with this museum, what has
been the

48:59.203 --> 49:00.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
biggest surprise for you along
the way?

49:01.005 --> 49:04.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: I think I have
been stunned
by the excitement and the way
people really

49:04.441 --> 49:06.243 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
care.

49:06.277 --> 49:09.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are times I will walk in
an airport
and people will just sort of
give me the thumbs

49:09.914 --> 49:14.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up, or I will walk down the
street and church
ladies will come to me and say
they're praying

49:14.585 --> 49:16.420 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for me.

49:16.453 --> 49:19.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think the fact that this
means so much
to so many people has been the
biggest surprise

49:19.957 --> 49:21.892 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for me.

49:21.926 --> 49:26.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As with other
Smithsonian museums,
one building cannot begin to
hold its collection.

49:26.897 --> 49:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Conservator Antje Neumann has
helped preserve
the collection at the museum's
facility in

49:31.869 --> 49:33.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a Washington suburb.

49:33.704 --> 49:35.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTJE NEUMANN, Conservator,
National Museum
of African American History and
Culture: There's

49:35.472 --> 49:40.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
always the balance between
preservation and
exhibition, and allowing the
public to see

49:40.811 --> 49:46.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the national treasures, and then
also balancing
that with preserving it for
future generations.

49:46.450 --> 49:52.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's lovely to have a place to
highlight the
struggles, the causes and the
progression

49:52.590 --> 49:56.527 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that many people and the
contributions many
people have done in this
country.

49:56.560 --> 50:01.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It falls to Neumann
to repair
Shaquille O'Neal's size 20 shoe,
to prepare

50:01.599 --> 50:08.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a stool from Muhammad Ali's gym,
to restore
worn pages of the first book of
black poetry,

50:08.305 --> 50:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and to spiff up funk singer
Bootsy Collins'
bright yellow leather costume.

50:12.476 --> 50:17.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTJE NEUMANN: It just needs a
bit -- a little
bit of cleaning in order to make
it ready

50:17.081 --> 50:20.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for presentation, as it has been
used a lot
on stage.

50:20.684 --> 50:25.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Collins' outfit
occupies a place
of honor inside the new
building, which is

50:25.789 --> 50:27.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a work of art itself.

50:27.658 --> 50:34.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The corona, the signature
exterior feature,
is made of 230 tons of
bronze-colored aluminum

50:34.698 --> 50:38.168 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
panels, 3,600 in all.

50:38.202 --> 50:41.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lead architect Phil Freelon
oversaw the building's
striking design.

50:41.872 --> 50:46.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL FREELON, Lead Architect:
Many of the
buildings on the Mall are
marble, granite,

50:46.277 --> 50:48.679 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
concrete, lighter in color.

50:48.712 --> 50:52.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This building has a variation in
how it appears.

50:52.182 --> 50:57.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, on certain days, in certain
lighting conditions,
it can be very vibrant and
bright.

50:57.154 --> 51:01.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And other times of the day or in
the evening,
it is darker.

51:01.392 --> 51:06.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there is this interesting
dynamic of changing
appearance of the building.

51:06.497 --> 51:12.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Within view, the
Washington Monument
and even a glimpse of the White
House, which

51:12.336 --> 51:17.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michelle Obama famously noted
was itself built
by slaves.

51:17.141 --> 51:21.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bunch says this makes race an
integral part
of the American experience.

51:21.278 --> 51:26.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in this country, we are so
nervous about
talking about race, about
engaging.

51:26.550 --> 51:30.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We keep having national
conversations about
race, and it seems that this
building itself

51:30.854 --> 51:33.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is a big conversation.

51:33.057 --> 51:36.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you -- did you encounter
along the way
any resistance to the notion
that we talk

51:36.961 --> 51:39.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about Americans only by race?

51:39.263 --> 51:47.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: I think there was
fear that
we would be a place that might
be divisive,

51:47.204 --> 51:51.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that people wouldn't want to
talk about race,
and that we would force them to
talk about

51:51.942 --> 51:53.744 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
race.

51:53.777 --> 51:59.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there was a great
concern that, would
this just be a museum by black
people for

51:59.483 --> 52:01.251 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
black people?

52:01.285 --> 52:05.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we had to counter
that, both by
the kind of stories we told, by
the way we

52:06.023 --> 52:10.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tried to say, this is a story of
America through
an African-American lens.

52:10.828 --> 52:15.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Joyce Bailey's
mother could not
have foreseen this day, but she
did see the

52:15.232 --> 52:18.068 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
value of preserving black
history.

52:18.102 --> 52:24.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lois Alexander passed away in
2007, leaving
her daughter with a window into
history.

52:24.608 --> 52:27.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But didn't you feel a little
emotional about
letting it go?

52:27.378 --> 52:32.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOYCE BAILEY: I was very happy
about letting
it go, because I knew my
mother's legacy would

52:32.750 --> 52:33.717 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
continue.

52:33.751 --> 52:36.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Curators think about
legacy too.

52:36.487 --> 52:38.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lonnie Bunch is still looking
ahead.

52:38.389 --> 52:42.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LONNIE BUNCH: I want to make
sure that curators
50 years from now can tell the
story of today,

52:42.993 --> 52:44.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if that's what they want to
tell.

52:44.862 --> 52:50.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I hope this museum will
continue to evolve,
continue to change, because it
really has

52:50.834 --> 52:56.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be a place that is the great
convener,
that can bring anybody and
everybody into

52:56.073 --> 52:58.442 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a conversation around race.

52:58.475 --> 53:10.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: From groundbreaking
in 2012 to
open doors this week, America
preserved, America

53:10.721 --> 53:15.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
celebrated, right in the
nation's front yard.

